  "business_context": "Case records are the customer-service equivalent of Opportunity — each case represents one issue that's actively being worked toward resolution, with a status, an owner, a priority, an SLA, and a resolution narrative. Cases typically intake through multiple channels (email-to-case, web-to- case forms, phone, chat, social media) and route to the appropriate agent or team based on routing rules. The Case-vs-Opportunity split is conceptually clean: Opportunity tracks \"deal in pursuit\" (potential revenue), Case tracks \"issue in resolution\" (potential cost or risk to retention). HubSpot uses \"Ticket\" rather than \"Case\" but the model is identical. CiviCRM has Case as a general-purpose work-tracking entity (used for any multi-step workflow with a stakeholder, not just customer service — also used for grant-cycle tracking, advocacy campaigns, beneficiary case management). EspoCRM has Case as a standard CRM-module entity. Bloomerang and Attio have no native Case concept. When interviewing clients, surface \"Case\" by asking what kind of work needs to be tracked from intake through resolution: support tickets, benefit-eligibility reviews, grant applications, advocacy campaigns, multi-stakeholder coordination on individual problems. Different from Activity (single-touchpoint logging) and Opportunity (revenue-generating pursuit) — Case captures problem-solving work spanning multiple touchpoints over time. SLA tracking, escalation rules, and customer-portal visibility are the most-customized aspects in customer-service deployments.",
